<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
The rich get richer, and the poor get poorer.  It's seen everywhere, and even current trends are pointing in that direction.  Is it a good thing?  Is it a bad thing?  I dunno, but I think it's definately the obvious state of things.<P>Right now, the amount of Relic Keep guards a realm gets depends on how many relics they own.  They get less for the more relics they have.  That's kinda balancing, and it's nice so the powerful ones are weakened in that respect.  But that's the only sort of balance like that that I see...<P>They said they were planning to allow Bounty Points buy newer, stronger equipment.  Besides screwing over tradesmen, it also rewards the successful (read that as "powerful) people out in RvR.  Archers, Assassins, any 1-hit killers will be reaping new equipment, making them even stronger and *more* capable of gaining even more RPs and BPs, to get even better stuff, and....yeah.  You see how that cycle goes, don't you?<P>There's also word that RPs will be used to gain skills.  I doubt it'll be new skills, but rather it'll just let us train our skills more.  Ye all saw it in the new training box when you talk to your trainer, eh?  Again, this is just like the previous one on BPs....strong get stronger, weak get weaker.<P>Right now we have a Dungeon that provides uber-loot for the realm with the most keeps.  Are keeps harder to acquire?  Do they last a bit longer to a siege?  No, and no.  We saw RP Farming before, now we bear witness to Keep Farming.  It's been going on on Percival for the past few days, all three realms are divided; half the realm is out sacking keeps by the hour, while the other half is back camping the DF portal, waiting until the scales tip in their balance so they can flood in.  Again, it's a bonus to the strongest realm (at that hour); it follows all the previous trends of making the strong even stronger, but it goes beyond that.  By not making keeps harder to get or last longer, the shuffling around of keeps is an absurd event that occurs every hour, half an hour, or worse.<P>So the scales get whacked out of proportion as the strong ones are rewarded by added strength.  Something else I noticed that bothers me....everyone says how they *need* to get their new armor.  They *need* to get their Epic armor.  Why?  To compete.  To stand a chance.  Right now, the way it was hoped or envisioned (or so I believe) was that there would be a moderate average, and some people would be stronger than that average, and some people would be weaker.  If you didn't have your epic armor, and you meet an enemy that *did*, they would have an advantage that can be countered if you handle it properly (use terrain to give you an advantage, or something).  That's how it was envisioned.<P>Unfortunately, they didn't realize that the majority would work for the stronger stuff.  The majority would not be content with the normal stuff, but would work and expect to have the best items out there.  In practice, it is the majority out there wearing the uber-gear, and the "average" effectiveness of a class in RvR is based on them wearing all the best gear, so that anyone who doesn't have that gear is at a considerable disadvantage that cannot easily be countered.  This then drives all the masses to climb to the very top, so there is no "lesser, average, and stronger players", there's just the top being "average" and everyone not at the top being "lesser".<P>How do you fix this?  Do you make the Uber Gear harder to get?  I don't think so, people will still work for it as a whole.  Do you make the super gear not that wildly helpful, or make it only situationally helpful with perhaps weaknesses?  Maybe have some of that uber-gear be more effective in a Keep Defense (don't ask me how, heh), but make it normal in all other circumstances?  That way the only ones who would go to great lengths to get it are those who see themselves doing enough keep defenses so that it's worth it.  Are there any ways to really balance all that super gear out so people don't feel like they "need" that better armor when the only reason they need it is because, chances are, the enemy realms majority will be wearing that same level of armor?  <P>And as for the other rich getting richer or poor getting poorer aspect, is there a way to balance that out so the successful ones *do* get rewarded, but not by giving them an even stronger edge over their prey?
</FONT>
